40|$|In ancient Egypt, <b>food</b> <b>crises</b> {{were most}} often occasioned by bad harvests {{following}} low or destructive inundations. <b>Food</b> <b>crises</b> developed into famines when administrative officials—state or local—were unable to organize storage and redistribution systems. Food deprivation, aggravated by hunger-related diseases, led to increased mortality, migrations, and social collapse. In texts and representations, the famine motif {{is used as}} an expression of chaos, emphasizing the political and theological role of the king (or nomarch or god) as “dispenser of food. ...|$|R
