50|$|In 2008, {{as global}} food prices spiked, the {{remaining}} commodities (about 915,000 metric tons) were sold. Since then, the trust is solely a cash reserve, invested in low-risk, short-term securities or instruments. The trust allows the U.S. Agency for International Development’s (USAID) Office of Food for Peace (FFP) {{to respond to}} <b>food</b> <b>crises</b> in other countries and release and use funds for famine relief in cases where other resources are not available. Since it not longer holds commodities, it can respond to local <b>food</b> <b>crises</b> outside the US, but not to a global one that affects the USA itself. The trust is still active as of 2017.|$|R
